The C-I workflow — promotion from dev, to test, to prod. Let's walk the end-to-end shape, using GitHub Actions as the runner.

A developer commits and pushes, and opens a pull request. That triggers the first C-I stage: GitHub Actions runs validate and lint — bundle-validate against dev, test, and prod. Notice it validates all three targets, so you catch a prod-specific mistake before it ever merges. Then a human reviews the P-R and merges to main. The merge triggers the second stage: GitHub Actions deploys — bundle-deploy to test, then it runs a smoke job and waits for green, and only then does it bundle-deploy to prod. That smoke-test gate is what keeps a bad build out of production.

Look at the minimal deploy workflow. It triggers on push to main. It sets three environment secrets — databricks-host, client-id, and client-secret — so the C-L-I can authenticate as a service principal. Then the steps check out the repo, install the C-L-I with databricks-slash-setup-cli, deploy to test, run the smoke-test job on test, and deploy to prod. That's a complete, if minimal, pipeline.

And here's what the exam expects you to recognise: the split between the two commands. Validate runs on every pull request. Deploy runs on merge to main, scoped per target, and usually gated behind a smoke test before prod. One more thing that's genuinely important — both commands are identical regardless of cloud or workspace. Whether you're on A-W-S, Azure, or G-C-P, whether it's dev or prod, the target manifest changes but the C-L-I command does not. That uniformity is exactly what makes bundles portable.
